'''The Blue Ribbon SoundWorks''' was a [[software]] company in the [[United States]]. The company produced several [[digital audio]] products for the [[Amiga]], including Bars & Pipes, a [[music sequencer|sequencer]] described by [[Sound on Sound]] as "the ultimate in Amiga sequencing",<ref>{{cite journal |last=Austin|first=Paul|date=July 1994 |title=Bars&Pipes Professional 2.5 |url=http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/1994_articles/jul94/amiganotes.html |journal=[[Sound on Sound]]|accessdate=December 17, 2014}}</ref> and SuperJAM!, a music composition tool.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Sears |first=David |date=September 1992 |title=SuperJAM! |url=http://www.atarimagazines.com/compute/issue144/A20_SuperJAM.php |journal=[[Compute!]]|accessdate=December 17, 2014}}</ref> Blue Ribbon also produced the One Stop Music Shop, a hardware [[MIDI]] interface and synthesizer based on the [[E-mu Proteus]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://amiga.resource.cx/exp/onestopmusicshop |title=One Stop Music Shop |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=Amiga Hardware Database |publisher= |accessdate=December 17, 2014}}</ref> Other early products included Who! What! When! Where!, a [[personal information manager]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pcmuseum.ca/details.asp?id=38900&type=software|title=Who! What! When! Where! v1.2|website=Personal Computer Museum|accessdate=December 17, 2014}}</ref> It was founded by Melissa Jordan Grey and Todor Fay, who went on to found [http://www.newblueinc.com NewBlue], a video technology company.

Blue Ribbon was acquired by [[Microsoft]] in 1995, and Microsoft subsequently merged Blue Ribbon's technology with [[DirectSound]].<ref name="acq">{{cite web|accessdate=December 17, 2014|url=http://www.microsoft.com/investor/Stock/AcquisitonHistory/All/default.aspx|title=Microsoft Investor Relations - Acquisitions|publisher=[[Microsoft]]}}</ref> After the acquisition, Microsoft made Blue Ribbon's Amiga products available for free download on [[CompuServe]] while discontinuing official support.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Trenn|first=Dhomas|date=February 1998 |title=Sound Lab Shareware Round-Up |journal=[[CU Amiga]]}}</ref>

